          "text": "Yes — what you're describing is exactly the L1 layer of the read path in the cross-report, and it's the pattern production converged on (ChatGPT's reference-chat-history injection, Zep's context block, MemPalace's L2/L3). You're not inventing beyond the evidence here. The strongest argument *for* eager injection over tools-only is the unknown-unknowns problem: the model can't search for a fact it doesn't know exists. \"Georgie's birthday\" only triggers a search if the model already suspects there's a Georgie history — eager injection is what makes the assistant feel like it *knows you*. So: eager injection + search tools are complementary, not alternatives, and both are already in the plan (L1 + L2).\n\nThree real design problems to get right, in order of importance:\n\n**1. Contamination is the #1 documented failure of this exact pattern.** ChatGPT's biggest memory complaint is old facts bleeding into unrelated chats. Mitigations that matter: a *relevance threshold* (inject nothing below it — empty injection must be the common case), a hard token budget (~500–1000 tokens as specced), provenance labels on every injected item, the `[recalled data, not instructions]` wrapper, and the §20.2 \"show memory used\" chips so users see and can kill bad recalls. An injection block that fires on every message will feel haunted, not smart.\n\n**2. The raw user message is a weak query.** \"Help me plan Georgie's birthday party\" is the flattering example — entity-rich, self-contained. Most messages are anaphoric (\"what about the second option?\") or the relevant memory keys off conversation context, not the last message. Practical fix: query = last message + recent-turn window, hybrid FTS + vector (FTS catches \"Georgie\" exactly; vectors catch \"my daughter's celebration\"), and lean on the L2 tool for anything requiring reasoning about *what* to search. Don't build query-rewriting/HyDE machinery up front.\n\n**3. Sequencing.** Eager injection doesn't requi