          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a00d********639e</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********YMZA</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-llame--claude-worktrees-llm-assistant-memory-research/2048159c-169f-41a4-b16a-b40485311c31/tasks/a00d673ae5d98639e.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Analyze beads memory architecture\" finished</summary>\n<note>A task-notification fires each time this agent stops with no live background children of its own. The user can send it another message and resume it, so the same task-id may notify more than once.</note>\n<result># Beads (`bd`) — Architecture Report for Long-Term Agent Memory Research\n\n## 1. What IS this project\n\n**Identity.** This is confirmed to be Steve Yegge's beads project. The Go module is still `github.com/steveyegge/beads` (go.mod:1), and `docs********G.md:125` states explicitly: *\"The repository now lives under `gastownhall/beads`, but released Go modules still declare `github.com/steveyegge/beads` for compatibility.\"* `CHANGELOG.md:428` confirms *\"The repo move in v1.0.0 left these URLs stale\"* — i.e., the repo was relocated from `steveyegge/beads` to the `gastownhall` org during the 1.0.0 release.\n\n**Stack.** Go (1,517 `.go` files, 794 `_test.go` files, ~464K LOC). Storage is **Dolt** (a MySQL-wire-compatible, git-like versioned SQL database), not JSONL/SQLite/git-native as I initially hypothesized — SQLite was the *original* backend per the very first commit message (`git log` reverse), but the project migrated to Dolt as primary storage.\n\n**Maturity.** This local checkout's `main` branch has only 50 commits (2026‑07‑07 to 2026‑07‑09), which looks thin, but `CHANGELOG.md` reveals real project history: 114 tagged releases from `v0.1.0` (\"Initial Development\") to `v1.1.0` (stable, 2026‑07‑04), spanning **2025‑10‑12 → 2026‑07‑09** — a ~9 month project releasing roughly every 2–3 days. CI is heavy: 15 GitHub Actions workflows (`.github/workflows/`), including `main.yml` (37.8K), `pr.yml` (23.7K), `ci-measurements.yml` (29.1K), `nightly.yml`, `migration-test.yml`, `regression.yml`. Test-to-source file ratio is ~52%. This is a serious, actively engineered project, not a toy.\n\n**Positioning (its own words).** README.md:15: *\"Beads provides a persistent, structured memory for coding agents. It replaces messy markdown plans with a dependency-aware graph, allowing agents to handle long-horizon tasks without losing context.\"* `AGENTS.md:164`: *\"This project uses bd (beads) for ALL issue tracking. Do NOT use markdown TODOs, task lists, or other tracking methods.\"* `docs/FAQ.md:8`: *\"bd is a lightweight, Dolt-powered issue tracker designed for AI coding agents… so agents and humans can collaborate from the same task graph.\"* Note: it frames itself as replacing **markdown TODO/plan files**, not as a general \"agent memory\" system in the RAG/episodic sense — the `bd remember` subsystem (below) is the closer analog to what our platform means by \"memory.\"\n\n## 2. Core data model\n\n**Entity model.** Core types live in `internal/types/types.go` (per `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md:179-186`): `Issue`, `Dependency`, `Label`, `Comment`, `Event`. Issues (\"beads\") are the atomic unit; there is no separate \"memory\" entity beyond a flat key-value store (see §3).\n\n**Dependency types** (`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md:196-202`): `blocks` (X must close before Y; affects readiness), `parent-child` (hierarchical epic/subtask; children blocked if parent blocked; affects readiness), `related` (soft reference, does not affect readiness), `discovered-from` (found during work on parent; does not affect readiness — this is explicit agent-generated-issue provenance tracking).\n\n**Status lifecycle** (`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md:204-208, 240`): `open → in_progress → closed`, reopenable; full status vocabulary is `open, in_progress, blocked, deferred, closed, tombstone, pinned, hooked`. Soft-delete uses tombstone fields (`deleted_at`, `deleted_by`, `delete_reason`, `original_type`) — invalidate/mark, not hard-delete, for synced issues (`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md:263-268`).\n\n**Storage substrate &amp; sync/merge model.** Dolt is the source of truth, not git and not JSONL (`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md:12-40`, README.md:118-141). Two modes:\n- **Embedded** (default): in-process Dolt, single-writer, file-locking enforced, data in `.beads/embeddeddolt/` (README.md:118-125).\n- **Server**: external `dolt sql-server`, multi-writer capable, data in `.beads/dolt/` (README.md:134-148).\n\nDistributed writes are resolved via **content-hash-based IDs** rather than sequential IDs, specifically to avoid the classic \"two branches both create `bd-10`\" collision (`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md:78-124`): each issue gets a random-UUID-derived short hash ID (4→6 chars, progressively scaled), plus a content hash for change detection. Merge logic: same ID + same hash → skip; same ID + different hash → update (newer wins); no match → create. `bd export`/`.beads/issues.jsonl` is explicitly a portability/interchange artifact, **not** the source of truth or a full backup (README.md:129-131, 155-157) — this directly contradicts a naive \"git-native JSONL database\" mental model.\n\nConcurrency correctness under Dolt (which has **no real row locking** — `FOR UPDATE`/`SKIP LOCKED` are parse-only no-ops) is handled with a deliberate \"row_lock\" collision cell: every status/ownership/lease-mutating write rewrites a shared `row_lock` int64 to a fresh random value so that two writers touching *different* cells of the same row (e.g., a heartbeat vs. a close) are forced to collide and trigger Dolt's MySQL 1213/1205 serialization-conflict retry path instead of silently merging cell-by-cell (`internal/storage/issueops/lease.go:40-52`). `ClaimReadyIssue` and `HeartbeatIssue` both wrap writes in `withRetryTx` for exactly this reason (`internal/storage/dolt/issues.go:239-296`).\n\n**Agent interaction &amp; context injection.** Both CLI (Cobra commands, `cmd/bd/`) and MCP (`integrations/beads-mcp`, Python package `beads-mcp`) are supported. The project explicitly recommends CLI+hooks over MCP for context efficiency: *\"CLI + hooks: ~1-2k tokens; MCP Server: 10-50k tokens\"* (`website/docs/integrations/mcp-server.md`, Trade-offs table). MCP tools exposed: `beads_create`, `beads_list`, `beads_show`, `beads_update`, `beads_close`, `beads_ready`, `beads_sync`, `beads_dep_add`, `beads_dep_tree`.\n\nContext injection is **eager, at session start**, via `bd prime` (`cmd/bd/prime.go:83-120`), designed to run as a Claude Code / Gemini CLI / Codex SessionStart hook \"to prevent agents from forgetting bd workflow after context compaction.\" It has no pull-based \"ready-work query only\" mode by default in hooks; `bd ready` is a separate pull-style query agents call explicitly during work (`bd ready`, `bd show &lt;id&gt;`, `bd update &lt;id&gt; --claim`, README.md:41-44).\n\n**\"Ready work\" computation** is a deterministic offline SQL query, not a graph traversal in application code: `GetReadyWorkInTx` (`internal/storage/issueops/ready_work.go:93-140`) builds a `WHERE` predicate (`buildReadyWorkPredicates`, `ready_work.go:44-90`) that excludes issues blocked by open `blocks`/`parent-child` dependencies, computes transitive descendant sets for parent filters, and returns ordered issue IDs — advertised as completing \"in ~10ms, no network required\" (`docs/FAQ.md`, \"Deterministic Ready-Work Detection\").\n\n**Lifecycle/archival/compaction.** `bd prune --older-than 30d --force` permanently deletes closed non-ephemeral issues to shrink storage/exports; reference-aware protection skips closed issues still cited by open issues' description/notes/comments (README.md:159-179). Separately, **Molecules/Wisps** provide a compaction pattern purpose-built for agent execution traces: a \"molecule\" is a template workflow; spawning it creates ephemeral \"wisp\" child issues that track execution steps *locally only* — never synced, hard-deleted (not tombstoned) on `bd mol squash`, which compresses the wisp trace into one permanent \"digest\" issue (`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md:294-334`, `docs********S.md:136,234,282`). This is a genuine agent-memory pattern: cheap noisy local trace → compacted permanent summary, discarding raw steps.\n\n**Multi-user/multi-agent story.** Identity is just a free-text `actor`/`assignee` string plus git-author string for Dolt commits (`commitAuthorString()`, `internal/storage/dolt/issues.go:233,262`) — there is **no authentication, no RBAC, no ACL**. My search of `docs/*.md` for \"RBAC/permission/ACL\" turned up only file-permission and OS-signal references (`docs********K.md:49`), never access-control semantics. Coordination is via a **lease mechanism**: `ClaimReadyIssue` atomically claims + commits (`internal/storage/dolt/issues.go:239-269`); `HeartbeatIssue` refreshes `lease_expires_at` (`issues.go:274-296`); `DefaultLeaseTTL = 5 * time.Minute` with `bd reclaim` reverting stale-leased issues back to ready (`internal/storage/issueops/lease.go:19-23`). There's also a separate, coarser **`.beads/.exclusive-lock` file protocol** (holder/pid/hostname/JSON) for external tools like CI runners to fence off the whole database, with dead-process detection via `ESRCH`/`EPERM` signal checks (`docs********K.md:9-49`).\n\n## 3. The \"memory\" subsystem specifically (`bd remember`)\n\nThis is the piece closest to our two-tier facts model. It's a **flat key-value store**, not a table with signals/scoring/TTL:\n- `bd remember \"&lt;insight&gt;\" [--key K]`: writes `kvPrefix + memoryPrefix + key → content`; key auto-slugified from content if not given (`cmd/bd/memory.go:70-193`). Update-in-place semantics (no versioning/bi-temporal fields observed).\n- `bd recall &lt;key&gt;`, `bd forget &lt;key&gt;`, `bd memories [search]`: simple substring search over key/value (`memory.go:197-405`).\n- Injection: `bd prime` dumps **all** memories verbatim into the session-start context as a `## Persistent Memories` (or compact `## Memories`) markdown section, capped by `--max-memories`/`--max-memory-chars` (whole-memory boundaries, at least one always emitted) (`cmd/bd/prime.go:438-496`).\n\nNotably **absent** from this injection path: any \"recalled data, not instructions\" framing, provenance/citation of source, confidence/decay scoring, or contradiction handling — memories are raw prose headers dumped straight into the prompt (`prime.go:454-455,487`). There is no `access_count`/`confirmations`/`contradictions` equivalent, no usage-TTL decay, and no bi-temporal `valid_at`/`invalid_at` — this is explicit-facts-only, with no consolidation pipeline or episodic-retrieval-over-raw-history layer at all.\n\n## 4. What's worth adopting\n\n- **Typed dependency semantics with readiness impact** (`blocks`/`parent-child` affect ready-work; `related`/`discovered-from` don't) is a clean, minimal vocabulary worth mirroring for goals/todos, especially `discovered-from` as first-class agent-generated-issue provenance (`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md:196-202`).\n- **Deterministic ready-work as a plain indexed SQL WHERE clause**, not app-level graph traversal — validates doing this in Postgres directly rather than building a separate dependency-resolution service (`ready_work.go:93-140`).\n- **Wisp→digest compaction pattern**: cheap, private, never-synced execution trace collapsed into one durable summary issue on completion — directly maps to \"compaction of closed issues/runs into summaries\" and is a good template for compacting pg-boss job traces into a durable audit record (`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md:294-334`).\n- **Lease + heartbeat + reclaim** for agent-run ownership (`DefaultLeaseTTL`, `HeartbeatIssue`, stale-lease reclaim) is a solid, proven pattern for our durable pg-boss agent runs (`internal/storage/issueops/lease.go:19-52`).\n- **Reference-aware pruning** (don't hard-delete an issue still cited elsewhere) is a good invariant to borrow for our invalidate-don't-delete facts table (README.md:169-179).\n\n## 5. Anti-examples / mismatches\n\n- **Git/Dolt-as-database, single-tenant-per-repo**: the whole model assumes one team/one Dolt DB per project clone; there is no multi-tenant isolation, no RLS analog, and identity is an unauthenticated free-text string — the opposite of our FORCE-RLS requirement.\n- **No access control whatsoever** — confirmed by direct grep; anyone with write access to the Dolt DB (or the exclusive-lock file) can read/write/delete anything.\n- **Eager, unframed memory injection**: `bd prime` dumps all memories as raw markdown into the system context with no \"this is recalled data, not instructions\" guardrail and no citation/verification step — exactly the anti-pattern our recall-time framing and plural-citation design are meant to avoid.\n- **No scoring/decay/bi-temporal model** in `bd remember` — it's simpler than even our \"signals-first\" deferred-scoring plan; nothing to adopt there beyond the CLI ergonomics.\n\n## 6. Honest verdict\n\nBeads is genuine, substantial engineering — 464K LOC, 52% test-file ratio, 15 CI workflows, 114 releases in 9 months, and non-trivial distributed-systems work (hash-ID collision avoidance, Dolt row-lock collision forcing, lease-based claiming) — this is not hype. But its \"memory\" framing is narrower than ours: it replaces *markdown TODO files* with a dependency graph plus a flat, unscoped key-value note store; it has no episodic/verbatim-history retrieval, no bi-temporal facts, no scoring, no multi-tenant access control, and no safe-framing of injected content. For our platform it's most useful as a reference for the **goals/todos entity model** (typed dependencies, ready-work SQL, lease-based agent-run ownership, wisp→digest compaction) — not as a reference for the **memory/recall architecture**, where our two-tier + bi-temporal + RLS + citation design is already meaningfully more rigorous.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>162723</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>31</tool_uses><duration_ms>296250</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>",
