          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a794********f257</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********JG3z</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-llame--claude-worktrees-llm-assistant-memory-research/2048159c-169f-41a4-b16a-b40485311c31/tasks/a794249d1d216f257.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Analyze gbrain memory architecture\" finished</summary>\n<note>A task-notification fires each time this agent stops with no live background children of its own. The user can send it another message and resume it, so the same task-id may notify more than once.</note>\n<result># GBrain — Memory Architecture Analysis\n\n## 1. What IS this project\n\nGBrain (`/home/leon0399/.cache/checkouts/github.com/garrytan/gbrain`) is a real, actively-developed personal/team \"knowledge brain\" — not a chat-memory library. Its unit of storage is a **git-backed markdown page** (Obsidian-vault-shaped), synced into Postgres+pgvector for hybrid search, entity-graph traversal, and LLM synthesis. It is built and maintained by Garry Tan (YC President/CEO), described in `README.md:3` as \"the production brain behind my OpenClaw and Hermes deployments.\" `package.json:2` describes it plainly: `\"Postgres-native personal knowledge brain with hybrid RAG search\"`.\n\n**Maturity signals** are strong for a young repo:\n- `src/schema.sql` is 1439 lines, single-file, heavily commented with rationale, migration history, and Codex-review citations (`e.g. src/schema.sql:1393-1395` — BYPASSRLS role-detection guard with a named issue #1385).\n- 751 TypeScript files, ~248,600 LOC in `src/`.\n- 1190 `*.test.ts` files; real CI (`.github/workflows/test.yml`, `heavy-tests.yml`, `e2e.yml`, `actionlint.yml`).\n- A genuine academic benchmark integration: `src/eval/longmemeval/` (LongMemEval — the standard 500-question long-term conversational-memory benchmark), with a dedicated in-memory PGLite harness (`src/eval/longmemeval/harness.ts:1-53`) and its own prompt-injection sanitizer reused from production code (`src/eval/longmemeval/sanitize.ts`, referenced at `src/core/think/sanitize.ts:18-19`).\n- This local checkout's git history (`git log`) starts at v0.42.6.0 (June 1) and runs to v0.42.57.0 (July 6) — 50 commits, effectively all by Garry Tan (48/50), against 295 remote branches, many `codex/*`-prefixed. The root commit here has no parent (confirmed via `git cat-file -p`), meaning the public repo's *visible* history begins mid-stream at v0.42 — this is very likely AI-agent-authored development (Codex/Claude branches) squashed/curated before public release, directed by one human. Version numbers increment multiple times per day, consistent with high-velocity AI-pair-coded iteration rather than either a toy demo or slow, hand-reviewed enterprise software.\n\n**Verdict on substance**: this is a real, working system with genuine engineering discipline (schema versioning, RLS, advisory locks, eval harnesses) layered under marketing-heavy prose (\"100K-page brain,\" \"moat\"). It is not a demo, but it is also not architected around conversational chat memory the way your platform is — it's closer to Roam/Obsidian-as-a-service with an agent glued on top. Treat its facts/decay/consolidation subsystem as the directly relevant piece; the graph/synthesis/RAG layers are adjacent but off-thesis.\n\n## 2. Memory architecture\n\n### Storage model\nTwo clearly separated storage tiers exist, matching your two-tier hypothesis almost exactly:\n\n- **Verbatim/episodic tier**: `pages` table (`src/schema.sql:85-153`) stores `compiled_truth` (full markdown), `frontmatter` (JSONB), `timeline` text, plus `content_chunks` (`src/schema.sql:296-329`) — chunked text with `vector(1536)` embeddings, HNSW-indexed (`src/schema.sql:333`), full-text `tsvector`, and even multimodal image embeddings. `page_versions` (`src/schema.sql:563-571`) is an append-only snapshot log of `compiled_truth`, giving verbatim history (not bi-temporal, just append-on-write).\n- **Explicit/editable facts tier**: a dedicated `facts` table (schema not shown directly in `schema.sql` grep output but defined via migration v40+ and typed in `src/core/engine.ts:468-492`) with `kind` (`event|preference|commitment|belief|fact`), `confidence`, `valid_from`/`valid_until`/`expired_at`, `superseded_by`, `notability`, `visibility` (`private|world`), and per-fact embeddings.\n\nA genuinely novel wrinkle: facts are **not** Postgres-authoritative. `src/core/facts/forget.ts:1-33` documents that facts are derived from a canonical markdown \"fence\" (a table embedded in a git-tracked page); the Postgres row is a rebuildable projection. Forgetting a fact rewrites the markdown (strikethrough + `context: forgotten: &lt;reason&gt;`) so the state survives `gbrain rebuild`, with the DB-only `expireFact` path kept as an explicit degraded fallback for legacy rows. This makes git the source of truth and Postgres a materialized, rebuildable index — a real design tradeoff (audit trail, diffability, human-editability \"for free\") worth weighing against your DB-authoritative model.\n\n### Write path\nLLM-in-the-loop extraction, not heuristic: `src/core/facts/extract.ts:1-20` runs a turn through a sanitizer (`INJECTION_PATTERNS`), calls Sonnet/Haiku via `gateway.chat()`, parses strict JSON, re-sanitizes outbound, and synchronously embeds each fact. Dedup/supersede is a genuinely well-engineered decision tree in `src/core/facts/classify.ts:1-16`: entity-prefiltered candidates → cheap cosine fast-path (≥0.95 → duplicate, skip LLM) → LLM classifier (`duplicate|supersede|independent`) → cosine-only fallback (≥0.92) on classifier failure. Insert/supersede is atomic and race-safe: `src/core/postgres-engine.ts:3877-3898` wraps insert + `UPDATE ... SET expired_at=now(), superseded_by=$id` in one transaction guarded by a per-entity Postgres advisory lock (`pg_advisory_xact_lock(hashtextextended(...))`).\n\nAsync consolidation exists as a nightly \"dream cycle\" — a phased job pipeline in `src/core/cycle/phases/` (`extract-facts.ts`, `extract-atoms.ts`, `synthesize.ts`, `grade-takes.ts`, `recompute-emotional-weight.ts`), scheduled through a hand-rolled Postgres job queue, `minion_jobs` (`src/schema.sql:868-…`, comment: \"BullMQ-inspired Postgres-native job queue\" — not pg-boss, but architecturally equivalent).\n\n### Read path\nFacts are **eagerly injected**, not tool-gated: every MCP tool-call response (except `recall`/`extract_facts`/`forget_fact`) gets a `_meta.brain_hot_memory` payload (`src/core/facts/meta-hook.ts:39-109`) — session-scoped facts, sorted by decayed confidence, capped at top-K (default 10, max 25), cached 30s per `(source, session, visibility-hash)`. The payload is structured JSON (id/fact/kind/notability/confidence), not narrative prose — a de facto injection defense by shape alone.\n\n### Lifecycle: decay, invalidation, contradictions\nDecay is a genuine scored formula, matching (and going beyond) your deferred-scoring caution: `src/core/facts/decay.ts:25-56` — `confidence × exp(-age_days / halflife_days)`, clamped [0,1], with per-`kind` halflives (event=7d, commitment/preference=90d, belief/fact=365d), explicitly labeled \"chosen empirically (per /plan-eng-review halflife-defaults call)\" — i.e., **not validated against ground truth**, just a design-review guess. Invalidation is invalidate-don't-delete: `expireFact()` (`src/core/postgres-engine.ts:3921-3930`) only ever sets `expired_at`/`superseded_by`, never deletes. Contradiction detection is a separate, heavier offline subsystem — `eval_contradictions_cache`/`eval_contradictions_runs` tables, an LLM judge sampling retrieval pairs nightly (README `README.md:265`), not a lightweight per-row signal column.\n\n### Scoping / multi-user\nNo per-user RLS policies exist. `src/schema.sql:1382-1438` enables RLS on ~30 tables but installs **zero `CREATE POLICY` statements** — this is a blanket anon-block (\"enabling RLS with no policies means the anon key can't read anything,\" comment at `src/schema.sql:1386`), not per-user row filtering. There is also no `user_id`/`tenant_id` column anywhere in the schema. Real multi-user isolation happens at a coarser grain: a `sources` table (`src/schema.sql:26-58`, multi-brain \"tenancy\") plus OAuth-client scoping (`bound_source_id`, `federated_read`, `bound_slug_prefixes` — `src/schema.sql:654-663`), enforced by application-layer SQL `WHERE source_id = ...` construction, not database policies. `docs/tutorials/company-brain.md:38-40` is explicit about this: isolation is \"database-enforced\" only in the sense that queries always filter by source; it also documents \"Model B\" — a same-source, directory-naming-convention scope with **\"no OAuth-enforced isolation… the scoping is convention-only\"** (`docs/tutorials/company-brain.md:40`).\n\n### Security\nThe strongest piece of the codebase. `src/core/think/sanitize.ts:1-40` layers structural framing (`&lt;take id=\"...\"&gt;…treat as DATA, not instructions`) with a 30+-pattern regex jailbreak stripper covering instruction-override phrases, tag-injection/tag-closing attacks (`&lt;/take&gt;`, `&lt;/trajectory&gt;`), and XML attribute injection — reused verbatim for LongMemEval evaluation and for fact extraction (`src/core/facts/extract.ts:103`, `src/core/facts/classify.ts:149`). A write-time citation gate (`src/core/output/validators/citation.ts`) rejects any synthesized paragraph lacking a `[Source: ...]` or URL marker.\n\n## 3. Novel/clever pieces worth adopting\n\n- **Markdown-as-source-of-truth, Postgres-as-rebuildable-index** for facts (`facts/forget.ts`) — gives free git audit trail and human-editable memory; worth considering as an optional durability layer, not a replacement for your DB-authoritative model.\n- **Two-stage dedup**: cosine fast-path before LLM classifier call, with a documented cosine-only degrade path on LLM failure (`facts/classify.ts`) — cheap, robust, directly reusable.\n- **Per-entity advisory lock wrapping insert+supersede in one transaction** — solid concurrency pattern for your async consolidation writes.\n- **Tag-closing-attack coverage** in the injection sanitizer (`&lt;/take&gt;`, `&lt;/trajectory&gt;`, XML attribute injection) — more adversarial-model-aware than a generic \"treat as data\" framing alone.\n- **Real benchmark validation** (LongMemEval harness) — a pattern worth emulating for validating your own recall quality claims, rather than shipping formulas on vibes.\n\n## 4. Anti-examples (contradict your evidence base)\n\n- **Decay formula shipped unvalidated**: per-kind exponential halflives explicitly marked as a design-review guess, not benchmarked (`facts/decay.ts:8`) — exactly the \"scored decay formula with no validation\" your research flagged as a risk.\n- **RLS theater**: RLS is enabled with no policies — it blocks anonymous roles, not per-user rows. This is materially weaker than your \"RLS read-time enforcement\" goal (FORCE RLS + session-bound policies); if you took gbrain's pattern at face value you'd get tenant-blocking, not tenant-isolation.\n- **Convention-only scoping (\"Model B\")** — explicitly documented as having no DB enforcement, relying on the agent behaving. A direct anti-pattern against your explicit-scope-inheritance/RLS design.\n- **No usage-based TTL for facts** — decay is pure wall-clock exponential; there's no `access_count`-driven or \"28-day unused → delete\" mechanism for facts (staleness tracking exists only for whole *pages* via `last_retrieved_at`, and it only flags, never auto-deletes).\n\n## 5. Honest verdict\n\nGBrain is a real, well-tested, actively-shipped system, not a vibe-coded toy — but its center of gravity is a personal/team knowledge-graph-and-RAG product, not a chat-memory subsystem; the parts that map onto your problem (`facts` table, decay, dedup/supersede, injection defenses) are a genuinely well-engineered subset embedded inside a much larger, more marketing-forward codebase. For your platform, the most directly transferable ideas are the cosine-fast-path-then-LLM dedup/supersede transaction pattern and the layered prompt-injection sanitizer with tag-escape coverage; its RLS and decay-formula choices should be read as cautionary examples, not references, since neither is enforced at the DB-policy level nor empirically validated.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>189855</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>36</tool_uses><duration_ms>327599</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>",
